 from region to region in the areas we inhabit. The book closes with chapters on how human cultures have affected each other’s geographic distributions, how non-human species have influenced human distribution, and how humans have reduced the ranges of many other species while increasing the ranges of others. Throughout, Harcourt compares what we understand of human biogeography to non-human primate biogeography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aBiogeography. 0aHuman geography. 0aPhysical anthropology. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Geography.2bisacsh  aanthropology books.  abeginning of mankind.  abiology and anthropology.  abiology and geography.  aclimate change.  acultural diversity.  aearth and humans.  aearth sciences.  aecology experts.  aevolution of man.  aevolution of mankind.  aevolution.  aevolutionary anthropologist.  ageography.  ahuman anatomy.  ahuman cultures.  ahuman distribution.  ahuman diversity.  ahuman evolution.  ahuman interaction.  ahuman origins.  ahuman physiology.  ahuman population.  ahuman primate.  ahuman species.  aphysical anthropology.  apopulation density.  aprimates and apes.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095177840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520951778423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520951778/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles